came Toryism and Puritanism became Whiggism; how the power of churchmen was challenged by virulent anticlericalism; how the verities of "divine right" theory revived and collapsed. Providing a distinctive account of English thought in the era between the two revolutions of the Stuart century, "Contesting the English Polity, 1660-1688" discusses the ideological foundations of emerging party politics, and the deep intellectual roots of competing visions for the commonwealth, placing the power of religion, and the taming of religion, squarely alongside constitutional battles within secular politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and statexHistoryy17th centuryzEngland. 0aChurch polityxHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Stuart Era (1603-1714).2bisacsh  aEnlightenment.  aPuritan.  aReformation.  aRoyalist.  aTory.  aWhig.  aanticlericalism.  adivine right.  aseventeenth century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311142849940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800106666?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800106666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800106666/original  a978-3-11-142849-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles